# oclif Development Standards

Use oclif-native patterns for all CLI work in this repository.

## Command Structure

- Implement commands under `src/commands/**` and export a class extending `Command` from `@oclif/core`.
- Define `static description`, `static examples`, `static flags`, and `static args` for every user-facing command.
- Keep command behavior in `async run()` and avoid side effects at module top-level.

## UX and Help

- Write clear help text and examples that match the real command usage.
- Prefer oclif parser/flags APIs instead of custom `process.argv` parsing.
- Keep output deterministic and concise; use `this.log()` for normal output and `this.warn()` for non-fatal warnings.

## Error Handling

- Throw meaningful errors in command logic and let oclif render failures consistently.
- Do not swallow exceptions silently.

## Examples

```ts
// Good: oclif-native command shape
export default class HelloWorld extends Command {
  static description = 'Say hello world'
  static examples = ['<%= config.bin %> hello world']
  static flags = {}
  static args = {}
  async run(): Promise<void> {
    this.log('hello world')
  }
}
```

```ts
// Avoid: bypassing oclif parsing/help system
const args = process.argv.slice(2)
console.log(args.join(' '))
```
